            Gadgets</font></h1>
        <hr>
        <h2 style="margin-top: 0cm; margin-bottom: 0.53cm"><font color="#000000">What
            are Gadgets?</font></h2>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0.53cm"><font color="#000000">In </font><strong><font
              color="#000000">Moksha</font></strong><font color="#000000">, a </font><strong><font
              color="#000000">Gadget</font></strong><font color="#000000"> is
            just about anything you see on the desktop. </font><strong><font color="#000000">Gadgets</font></strong><font
            color="#000000"> are what other operating systems call "Applets" or
            "Widgets": small programs that do one thing and do it well. Several
          </font><strong><font color="#000000">Gadgets</font></strong><font color="#000000">
            are installed by default. </font> </p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0.53cm"><font color="#000000"><font face="ubuntu, Tahoma, Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">M</font></font><font
            color="#000000">ost </font><strong><font color="#000000">Gadgets</font></strong><font
            color="#000000"> can be placed either directly on the desktop or
            onto a <a href="shelves.html">Shelf</a>, however, there are a few </font><strong><font
              color="#000000">Gadgets</font></strong><font color="#000000">
            (like </font><em><font color="#000000">Systray</font></em><font color="#000000">)
            that can </font><em><font color="#000000">only</font></em><font color="#000000">
            be placed on a </font><strong><font color="#000000">Shelf</font></strong><font
            color="#000000">. </font> </p>
